            "len": 1135,
            "post_value": "The one I'm most proud of at Microsoft is the rack-level resilience testing program I pioneered on Azure. There was no playbook for it - I defined the capability from scratch, drove it through engineering and cross-org alignment, and delivered a working program in 4 months with a 94% recovery rate. That work surfaced real hardware defects that shaped the platform's long-term reliability strategy. The speed and quality of that delivery earned executive visibility and became a model for how Azure approached proactive resilience testing going forward.\n\nThe second is from my first PM internship at Microsoft, where I built the case for a unified automation prioritization framework across 140+ teams and secured cross-functional buy-in on it. That work generated $3M in accelerated revenue and helped launch cloud regions 28% faster by translating messy, distributed operational pain into a clear product direction leadership could act on. Both examples come back to the same thing: taking a complex, ambiguous problem, moving fast, and delivering something that actually moved the business - not just a feature, but a real outcome."
